Let’s imagine legacy payment code like this:

```
if(type == "CARD") processCard();
else if(type == "UPI") processUPI();
else if(type == "WALLET") processWallet();
```

This grows poorly because each new payment adds branching.

Strategy refactor:

Interface:
```
interface PaymentStrategy {
    void pay(double amount);
}
```

Implementations:
```
class CardPayment implements PaymentStrategy {
    public void pay(double amount) { }
}

class UpiPayment implements PaymentStrategy {
    public void pay(double amount) { }
}
```

Selector:
```
class PaymentProcessor {
    private PaymentStrategy strategy;

    public PaymentProcessor(PaymentStrategy strategy) {
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    public void process(double amount) {
        strategy.pay(amount);
    }
}
```

Time Complexity:
Both approaches execute payment in O(1), but conditional chains grow toward O(k) where k = number of payment types. Strategy keeps selection constant once injected.

Also, whenever introducing new strategies like this, write unit tests per strategy implementation to verify behavior independently. This prevents regressions while extending payment methods.

Consider Fibonacci — a classic expensive recursive calculation.

Naive recursion:
```
int fib(int n) {
  if(n <= 1) return n;
  return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}
```

Time Complexity:
This runs in O(2^n) because each call recomputes overlapping subproblems repeatedly.

Memoized version:
```
Map<Integer, Integer> cache = new HashMap<>();

int fib(int n) {
  if(n <= 1) return n;
  if(cache.containsKey(n)) return cache.get(n);

  int result = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
  cache.put(n, result);
  return result;
}
```

Time Complexity becomes O(n) since each value computes once.

Whenever introducing memoization like this, write tests verifying correctness across edge cases (n=0, n=1, large n). Tests ensure optimization doesn’t alter expected results while improving performance.

Suppose legacy code searches users repeatedly:

```
User findUser(List<User> users, String id) {
  for(User u : users) {
    if(u.getId().equals(id)) return u;
  }
  return null;
}
```

Time Complexity:
Each lookup is O(n). Multiple lookups quickly become expensive.

Refactor using HashMap:
```
Map<String, User> userMap = new HashMap<>();
for(User u : users) {
  userMap.put(u.getId(), u);
}

User findUser(String id) {
  return userMap.get(id);
}
```

Lookup complexity becomes O(1) average time after an initial O(n) preprocessing step.

When implementing this optimization, write tests verifying lookup correctness, handling of missing IDs, and duplicate handling behavior. Tests ensure functional parity while improving performance.
